 s: Employment / Payrolls / Labour Force\n\n• Measures: Change in emplo
 yment\, unemployment\, participation and labour-market strength.\n\n• 
 Usual market effect: Stronger-than-forecast jobs data is usually bullish
  for the local currency and bearish for bonds if it increases rate-hike 
 expectations.\n\n• Why traders care: Jobs data is a major driver of in
 terest-rate expectations\, consumer spending expectations and recession-
 risk pricing.\n\n• Frequency: Monthly.\n\n• Notes: For the US\, Non-
 Farm Payrolls is one of the most market-moving releases. For Australia\,
  Labour Force data is important for RBA expectations.\n\n• Acronyms: N
 FP = Non-Farm Payrolls\; ABS = Australian Bureau of Statistics\; BLS = B
